            <h3>NFL Announces Amazon Prime Video as Home of Thursday Night Football Beginning in 2022 <span><time datetime="2021-05-03">May 3, 2021</time></span></h3>

            

        </div> <!-- END CONTENT -->
    </div> <!-- END content-block -->



        <div class="content-block article-half ">
            <div class="content">

<p>The NFL announced that Amazon Prime Video will be the exclusive home of Thursday Night Football beginning in the 2022 season. Amazon will distribute primetime's second most-watched show across hundreds of compatible digital devices. The NFL's original agreement with Amazon, <a href="https://operations.nfl.com/updates/football-ops/nfl-announces-long-term-broadcast-deal-to-enhance-fan-experience/">announced as part of a larger series of media distribution deals this past March</a>, had Amazon Prime Video hosting Thursday Night Football starting with the 2023 season.</p>
<p>As a result, the 2021 season will be the last for Thursday Night Football on FOX. FOX will continue to produce the National Football Conference (NFC) package of Sunday afternoon games with a focus on America's Game of the Week, the most-watched show across television for the last 12 seasons and the most-watched NFL window for the last 20 seasons.</p>
<p>The NFL and Amazon first partnered on Thursday Night Football <a href="https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NATIONAL-FOOTBALL-LEAGUE-AND-AMAZON-PRIME-ANNOUNCE-STREAMING-PARTNERSHIP-FOR-THURSDAY-NIGHT-FOOTBALL.aspx">as part of a tri-cast distribution model during the 2017 season</a>, initially with CBS/NBC and then FOX starting in 2018.</p>
<p>The NFL continues to be the only sports league that delivers all its games – regular season and playoffs – on free, over-the-air television.</p>        </div>
            </div>


